    mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #4
    A    		 AUD Actual RVI (wk)
    = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(     AUD Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( AUD Appointments in MM, AUD Completing Rate,52)),52)
    Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
    Present In 1 View:
    • Model
    Used By
    • Average Actual RVI The average RVI across all four appointment types.
    Feedback Loops: 0 (0.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 0  [0,0]
    mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #5
    A    		 AUD Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
    = IF THEN ELSE(     AUD Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> AUD< AUD Minimum Time to Schedule, AUD Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> AUD))
    Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.
    Present In 1 View:
    • Model
    Used By
    • AUD Target New Patient Wait Time The acceptable average wait time for new patients to start Care Coordination, based on the team's data. The user can also enter their own new patient wait time goal.

    A    		 AUD Appointments for Existing Patients (appt/wk)
    = MIN(     AUD Desired Appointment Completion Rate, AUD Current Appointment Supply)
    Description: The number of appointments used by existing patients each week. The team either satisfies all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or uses all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply), leaving no appointments available for new patients. (appt/wk)
    Present In 1 View:
    • Model
    Used By
    • AUD Appointments Available for New Patients Appointments available for new patients is the remaining supply of appointments, after demand from existing patients is satisfied. The user can also set aside ADDITIONAL appointments specifically for new patients. It is constrained from going below zero.
    • AUD Completing Rate Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)

    A    		 AUD Effect of Wait Time on Referrals (Dmnl)
    = MIN((XIDZ(     AUD Perceived Wait Time, AUD Target New Patient Wait Time,1))^- AUD Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time,1)
    Description: When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

        mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #45
        C,G        		 AUD Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
        = GAME(1)
        Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
        Present In 1 View:
        • Model
        Used By

This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

        mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #85
        A        		 DEP Actual RVI (wk)
        = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(         DEP Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( DEP Appointments in MM, DEP Completing Rate,52)),52)
        Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
        Present In 1 View:
        • Model
        Used By
        • Average Actual RVI The average RVI across all four appointment types.
        Feedback Loops: 0 (0.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 0  [0,0]

        A        		 DEP Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
        = IF THEN ELSE(         DEP Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Dep< DEP Minimum Time to Schedule, DEP Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Dep))
        Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.
        Present In 1 View:
        • Model
        Used By
        • DEP Target New Patient Wait Time The acceptable average wait time for new patients to start Care Coordination, based on the team's data. The user can also enter their own new patient wait time goal.

            mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #126
            C,G            		 DEP Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
            = GAME(1)
            Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
            Present In 1 View:
            • Model
            Used By
            • DEP Effect of Wait Time on Referrals When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

            Description: When the team uses overtime, they have less time available for important, but non-patient-facing care tasks (e.g., appointment prep, charting, follow-up, reminder calls). The more overtime a team works, the greater this effect, and the more the missed appointment rate will increase, compared to the norm. This effect only applies to overtime: working lower than the official work hours does not influence providers or patients to come more regularly to their appointments. (pct)

            A            		 OtherNeeds Actual RVI (wk)
            = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(             OtherNeeds Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( OtherNeeds Appointments in MM, OtherNeeds Completing Rate,52)),52)
            Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
            Present In 1 View:
            • Model
            Used By
            • Average Actual RVI The average RVI across all four appointment types.

            A            		 OtherNeeds Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
            = IF THEN ELSE(             OtherNeeds Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Other< OtherNeeds Minimum Time to Schedule, OtherNeeds Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Other))
            Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

                mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #184
                C,G                		 OtherNeeds Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                = GAME(1)
                Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                Present In 1 View:
                • Model
                Used By

                mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #194
                A                		 OUD Actual RVI (wk)
                = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                 OUD Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( OUD Appointments in MM, OUD Completing Rate,52)),52)
                Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                Present In 1 View:
                • Model
                Used By
                • Average Actual RVI The average RVI across all four appointment types.
                Feedback Loops: 0 (0.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 0  [0,0]

                A                		 OUD Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
                = IF THEN ELSE(                 OUD Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> OUD< OUD Minimum Time to Schedule, OUD Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> OUD))
                Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

                Description: The number of appointments used by existing patients each week.                 • OUD Completing Rate Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)

                L                		 OUD Appointments in MM (appt)

                Description: The total number of medication management appointments on the calendar. (appts)
                Present In 1 View:
                • Model
                Used By
                • OUD Actual RVI The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                • OUD Desired Appointment Completion Rate The desired completion rate depends on the number of appointments to complete and the return visit interval that was used when those appointments were booked.

                    C,G                    		 OUD Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                    = GAME(1)
                    Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)

                    mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #244
                    C,G                    		 Sensitivity of Missed Appointments to Task Time (Dmnl )
                    = GAME(1)
                    Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect changes in time for non-patient-facing care tasks has on missed appointments. A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between overbooks and missed appointments. A value below 1 indicates that patients are not sensitive to small changes in non-patient-facing task time; a value greater than 1 indicates that patients are very sensitive to small changes. Example: if a team is putting in 20% more hours per week than their official supply, then an exponent of "1" would indicate that the ratio of missed appointments to all appointments would also be 20% higher than before. A value of "0.5" would cause that same 20% increase in hours worked to have less of an effect (causing only a 9.5% increase in the missed appointment percentage). A value of "2" would cause that same 20% increase to have a greater effect (raising the missed appointment percentage by 44%). (pct)

                                                    A                                                    		 AUD Actual RVI (wk)
                                                    = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                                                     AUD Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( AUD Appointments in MM, AUD Completing Rate,52)),52)
                                                    Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).

                                                        C,G                                                        		 AUD Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                        = GAME(1)
                                                        Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                                                        Present In 1 View:

                                                        A                                                        		 DEP Actual RVI (wk)
                                                        = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                                                         DEP Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( DEP Appointments in MM, DEP Completing Rate,52)),52)
                                                        Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                        Present In 1 View:
                                                        • Model
                                                        Used By
                                                        • Average Actual RVI The average RVI across all four appointment types.

                                                        A                                                        		 DEP Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
                                                        = IF THEN ELSE(                                                         DEP Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Dep< DEP Minimum Time to Schedule, DEP Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Dep))
                                                        Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

                                                        A                                                        		 DEP Appointments for Existing Patients (appt/wk)
                                                        = MIN(                                                         DEP Desired Appointment Completion Rate, DEP Current Appointment Supply)
                                                        Description: The number of appointments used by existing patients each week. (appt/wk)
                                                        Present In 1 View:
                                                        • Model
                                                        Used By
                                                        • DEP Appointments Available for New Patients Appointments available for new patients is the remaining supply of appointments, after demand from existing patients is satisfied. The user can also set aside ADDITIONAL appointments specifically for new patients. It is constrained from going below zero.
                                                        • DEP Completing Rate Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)

                                                        F,A                                                        		 DEP Completing Rate (appt/wk)
                                                        =                                                         DEP Appointments for Existing Patients
                                                        Description: Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
                                                        Present In 1 View:
                                                        • Model
                                                        Used By
                                                        • DEP Actual RVI The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                        • DEP Appointments in MM The total number of medication management appointments on the calendar. (appts)
                                                        • DEP True Missed Appointment Rate The number of appointments that must be re-scheduled, as either the clinician or the patient missed the appointment, calculated from the team's data. (appts/wk)

                                                            C,G                                                            		 DEP Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                            = GAME(1)
                                                            Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                                                            Present In 1 View:
                                                            • Model
                                                            Used By
                                                            • DEP Effect of Wait Time on Referrals When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

                                                            A                                                            		 OtherNeeds Actual RVI (wk)
                                                            = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                                                             OtherNeeds Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( OtherNeeds Appointments in MM, OtherNeeds Completing Rate,52)),52)
                                                            Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).

                                                            Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

                                                            F,A                                                            		 OtherNeeds Completing Rate (appt/wk)
                                                            =                                                             OtherNeeds Appointments for Existing Patients
                                                            Description: Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
                                                            Present In 1 View:
                                                            • Model
                                                            Used By
                                                            • OtherNeeds Actual RVI The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                            • OtherNeeds Appointments in MM The total number of medication management appointments on the calendar. (appts)
                                                            • OtherNeeds True Missed Appointment Rate The number of appointments that must be re-scheduled, as either the clinician or the patient missed the appointment, calculated from the team's data. (appts/wk)

                                                                C,G                                                                		 OtherNeeds Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                                = GAME(1)
                                                                Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                                                                Present In 1 View:
                                                                • Model
                                                                Used By
                                                                • OtherNeeds Effect of Wait Time on Referrals When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

                                                                A                                                                		 OUD Actual RVI (wk)
                                                                = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                                                                 OUD Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( OUD Appointments in MM, OUD Completing Rate,52)),52)
                                                                Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                                Present In 1 View:

                                                                A                                                                		 OUD Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
                                                                = IF THEN ELSE(                                                                 OUD Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> OUD< OUD Minimum Time to Schedule, OUD Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> OUD))
                                                                Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

                                                                    C,G                                                                    		 OUD Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                                    = GAME(1)
                                                                    Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)

                                                                    A                                                                    		 Overbook Downside Onset Time (wk)
                                                                    =                                                                     Average Actual RVI
                                                                    Description: The time for sacrificing team coordination time and patient reminder calls for more face-to-face patient time to affect the missed appointment rate.
                                                                    Present In 1 View:
                                                                    • Model
                                                                    Used By
                                                                    • Effect of Task Time on Missed Appointments When the team uses overtime, they have less time available for important, but non-patient-facing care tasks (e.g., appointment prep, charting, follow-up, reminder calls). The more overtime a team works, the greater this effect, and the more the missed appointment rate will increase, compared to the norm. This effect only applies to overtime: working lower than the official work hours does not influence providers or patients to come more regularly to their appointments. (pct)
                                                                    Feedback Loops: 0 (0.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 0  [0,0]
                                                                    mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #244
                                                                    C,G                                                                    		 Sensitivity of Missed Appointments to Task Time (Dmnl )
                                                                    = GAME(1)
                                                                    Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect changes in time for non-patient-facing care tasks has on missed appointments. A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between overbooks and missed appointments. A value below 1 indicates that patients are not sensitive to small changes in non-patient-facing task time; a value greater than 1 indicates that patients are very sensitive to small changes. Example: if a team is putting in 20% more hours per week than their official supply, then an exponent of "1" would indicate that the ratio of missed appointments to all appointments would also be 20% higher than before. A value of "0.5" would cause that same 20% increase in hours worked to have less of an effect (causing only a 9.5% increase in the missed appointment percentage). A value of "2" would cause that same 20% increase to have a greater effect (raising the missed appointment percentage by 44%). (pct)
                                                                    Present In 1 View:
                                                                    • Model
                                                                    Used By
                                                                    • Effect of Task Time on Missed Appointments When the team uses overtime, they have less time available for important, but non-patient-facing care tasks (e.g., appointment prep, charting, follow-up, reminder calls). The more overtime a team works, the greater this effect, and the more the missed appointment rate will increase, compared to the norm. This effect only applies to overtime: working lower than the official work hours does not influence providers or patients to come more regularly to their appointments. (pct)

                                                                                      mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #4
                                                                                      A                                                                                      		 AUD Actual RVI (wk)
                                                                                      = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                                                                                       AUD Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( AUD Appointments in MM, AUD Completing Rate,52)),52)
                                                                                      Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                      • Average Actual RVI The average RVI across all four appointment types.
                                                                                      Feedback Loops: 0 (0.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 0  [0,0]
                                                                                      mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #5
                                                                                      A                                                                                      		 AUD Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
                                                                                      = IF THEN ELSE(                                                                                       AUD Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> AUD< AUD Minimum Time to Schedule, AUD Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> AUD))
                                                                                      Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.
                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                      • AUD Target New Patient Wait Time The acceptable average wait time for new patients to start Care Coordination, based on the team's data. The user can also enter their own new patient wait time goal.

                                                                                      A                                                                                      		 AUD Appointments Available for New Patients (appt/wk)
                                                                                      = MAX(                                                                                       AUD Current Appointment Supply- AUD Appointments for Existing Patients,0)+STEP( User AUD Appointment Slots Reserved for New Patients, Experiment Week)
                                                                                      Description: Appointments available for new patients is the remaining supply of appointments, after demand from existing patients is satisfied. The user can also set aside ADDITIONAL appointments specifically for new patients. It is constrained from going below zero.
                                                                                      Present In 1 View:

(pts/wk)

                                                                                      mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #7
                                                                                      A                                                                                      		 AUD Appointments for Existing Patients (appt/wk)
                                                                                      = MIN(                                                                                       AUD Desired Appointment Completion Rate, AUD Current Appointment Supply)
                                                                                      Description: The number of appointments used by existing patients each week. The team either satisfies all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or uses all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply), leaving no appointments available for new patients. (appt/wk)
                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                      • AUD Appointments Available for New Patients Appointments available for new patients is the remaining supply of appointments, after demand from existing patients is satisfied. The user can also set aside ADDITIONAL appointments specifically for new patients. It is constrained from going below zero.
                                                                                      • AUD Completing Rate Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
                                                                                      Feedback Loops: 1 (5.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 1  [4,4]
                                                                                      mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #8
                                                                                      L                                                                                      		 AUD Appointments in MM (appt)
                                                                                      = ∫(                                                                                       AUD Booking Rate+ AUD Rescheduling Rate)- AUD Completing Rate dt + AUD Initial Appointments
                                                                                      Description: The total number of medication management appointments on the calendar. (appts)
                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                      • AUD Actual RVI The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                                                      • AUD Desired Appointment Completion Rate The desired completion rate depends on the number of appointments to complete and the return visit interval that was used when those appointments were booked.

                                                                                      F,A                                                                                      		 AUD Completing Rate (appt/wk)
                                                                                      =                                                                                       AUD Appointments for Existing Patients
                                                                                      Description: Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)
                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                      • AUD Actual RVI The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                                                      • AUD Appointments in MM The total number of medication management appointments on the calendar. (appts)
                                                                                      • AUD True Missed Appointment Rate The number of appointments that must be re-scheduled, as either the clinician or the patient missed the appointment, calculated from the team's data. (appts/wk)
                                                                                      Feedback Loops: 1 (5.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 1  [4,4]

                                                                                      = (                                                                                       Official Total Appointment Supply* AUD % Slots Allocated to Each Diagnosis)+STEP( User AUD Overbooks, Experiment Week)- User AUD Appointment Slots Reserved for New Patients
                                                                                      Description: appts available for patient care depend on the total number of appointments offered, how those appointments are allocated across the diagnostic cohorts, and the additional appointments squeezed into the schedule through overbooking.
                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                      • AUD Appointments Available for New Patients Appointments available for new patients is the remaining supply of appointments, after demand from existing patients is satisfied. The user can also set aside ADDITIONAL appointments specifically for new patients. It is constrained from going below zero.
                                                                                      • AUD Appointments for Existing Patients The number of appointments used by existing patients each week. The team either satisfies all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or uses all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply), leaving no appointments available for new patients. (appt/wk)

                                                                                          C,G                                                                                          		 AUD Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                                                          = GAME(1)
                                                                                          Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                                                                                          Present In 1 View:
                                                                                          • Model
                                                                                          Used By
                                                                                          • AUD Effect of Wait Time on Referrals When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

                                                                                          A                                                                                          		 DEP Actual RVI (wk)
                                                                                          = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                                                                                           DEP Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( DEP Appointments in MM, DEP Completing Rate,52)),52)
                                                                                          Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                                                          Present In 1 View:
                                                                                          • Model
                                                                                          Used By
                                                                                          • Average Actual RVI The average RVI across all four appointment types.

                                                                                          A                                                                                          		 DEP Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
                                                                                          = IF THEN ELSE(                                                                                           DEP Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Dep< DEP Minimum Time to Schedule, DEP Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> Dep))
                                                                                          Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

                                                                                          • DEP Completing Rate Appointment completions are based on the team either satisfying all the demand from existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) or using all the supply (based on the Appointment Supply). If there is more demand than supply, then not all scheduled appointments will be seen in a timely manner, and Actual RVI will increase. This is different from a completed visit, as the appointment is still complete even if the patient no-shows. (appt/wk)

                                                                                              C,G                                                                                              		 DEP Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                                                              = GAME(1)
                                                                                              Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                                                                                              Present In 1 View:
                                                                                              • Model
                                                                                              Used By
                                                                                              • DEP Effect of Wait Time on Referrals When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

                                                                                              A                                                                                              		 OtherNeeds Actual RVI (wk)

                                                                                              Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).

                                                                                              Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients.                                                                                               • OtherNeeds Actual RVI The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                                                              • OtherNeeds Appointments in MM The total number of medication management appointments on the calendar. (appts)
                                                                                              • OtherNeeds True Missed Appointment Rate The number of appointments that must be re-scheduled, as either the clinician or the patient missed the appointment, calculated from the team's data. (appts/wk)

                                                                                                  C,G                                                                                                  		 OtherNeeds Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                                                                  = GAME(1)
                                                                                                  Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                                                                                                  Present In 1 View:
                                                                                                  • Model
                                                                                                  Used By
                                                                                                  • OtherNeeds Effect of Wait Time on Referrals When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

                                                                                                  A                                                                                                  		 OUD Actual RVI (wk)
                                                                                                  = MIN(IF THEN ELSE(                                                                                                   OUD Appointments in MM<0.05,0.01,XIDZ( OUD Appointments in MM, OUD Completing Rate,52)),52)
                                                                                                  Description: The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).

                                                                                                  A                                                                                                  		 OUD Adjusted New Patient Wait Time (median) (wk)
                                                                                                  = IF THEN ELSE(                                                                                                   OUD Referral Rate inferred from Data=0,0,IF THEN ELSE( Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> OUD< OUD Minimum Time to Schedule, OUD Minimum Time to Schedule, Data New Patient Wait Time (median) -> OUD))
                                                                                                  Description: It is possible for the estimate for the median new patient wait time to be zero, if the team sees many walk-in patients. However the Target New Patient Wait Time needs to be an average, thus a value of zero is not feasible. In these rare cases, we prevent the model from using a zero average wait time, instead using the Minimum Time to Schedule. If the relevant start rate is zero (indicating no patients follow this pathway), then the wait time is also set to zero.

                                                                                                      C,G                                                                                                      		 OUD Sensitivity of Referrals to Wait Time (Dmnl )
                                                                                                      = GAME(1)
                                                                                                      Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect increases in new patient wait time (or decreases in target wait time) have on referrals, where referrals drop as wait time increases (or the target wait time decreases). A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between wait time and referrals. A value of "1" indicates that if the new patient wait time doubles (relative to the new patient wait time goal), then referring providers will cut their care coordination referrals in half. For the same situation, a value of "0.5" would result in less of an effect (reducing the referral rate to 71% of its original value), and a value of "1.5" would result in a greater effect (reducing the referral rate to less than 35% of its original value). (pct)
                                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                                      • OUD Effect of Wait Time on Referrals When the wait time to start medication management increases above the target wait time for patients with a specific diagnosis, referring providers will be less likely to refer a new patient with that diagnosis. This effect only applies to above-target wait times: lower than expected new patient wait times do not increase referrals above the norm. (pct)

                                                                                                      mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #244
                                                                                                      C,G                                                                                                      		 Sensitivity of Missed Appointments to Task Time (Dmnl )
                                                                                                      = GAME(1)
                                                                                                      Description: This controls the magnitude of the effect changes in time for non-patient-facing care tasks has on missed appointments. A value of "zero" implies that there is no relationship between overbooks and missed appointments. A value below 1 indicates that patients are not sensitive to small changes in non-patient-facing task time; a value greater than 1 indicates that patients are very sensitive to small changes. Example: if a team is putting in 20% more hours per week than their official supply, then an exponent of "1" would indicate that the ratio of missed appointments to all appointments would also be 20% higher than before. A value of "0.5" would cause that same 20% increase in hours worked to have less of an effect (causing only a 9.5% increase in the missed appointment percentage). A value of "2" would cause that same 20% increase to have a greater effect (raising the missed appointment percentage by 44%). (pct)
                                                                                                      Present In 1 View:
                                                                                                      • Model
                                                                                                      Used By
                                                                                                      • Effect of Task Time on Missed Appointments When the team uses overtime, they have less time available for important, but non-patient-facing care tasks (e.g., appointment prep, charting, follow-up, reminder calls). The more overtime a team works, the greater this effect, and the more the missed appointment rate will increase, compared to the norm. This effect only applies to overtime: working lower than the official work hours does not influence providers or patients to come more regularly to their appointments. (pct)

                                                                                                        = 0
                                                                                                        Description: Selecting the Existing Patient Return-to-clinic Visit Interval (RVI) mode prioritizes the existing patients RVI estimated from team data, and only starts new patients in remaining open slots after the existing patient RVI, appointment supply, and missed appointments are all taken into account.                                                                                                         Type
                                                                                                        		 Variable Name And Description
                                                                                                        mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #8
                                                                                                        L                                                                                                        		 AUD Appointments in MM (appt)
                                                                                                        = ∫(                                                                                                         AUD Booking Rate+ AUD Rescheduling Rate)- AUD Completing Rate dt + AUD Initial Appointments
                                                                                                        Description: The total number of medication management appointments on the calendar. (appts)
                                                                                                        Present In 1 View:
                                                                                                        • Model
                                                                                                        Used By
                                                                                                        • AUD Actual RVI The average wait time for new patients is based on the number of patients waiting and how many start care coordination each week (based on Little’s Law). If there is more demand for completing appointments than there is available capacity, then actual return visit interval will increase, even if the desired RVI doesn't change. If the completing appointment rate drops to zero, then the wait is technically infinite. In the model, appointments are never cancelled due to high wait times, but for ease of display, Actual RVI is capped at 12 months (52 weeks).
                                                                                                        • AUD Desired Appointment Completion Rate The desired completion rate depends on the number of appointments to complete and the return visit interval that was used when those appointments were booked.
                                                                                                        Feedback Loops: 1 (5.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 1  [4,4]
                                                                                                        mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #9
                                                                                                        L                                                                                                        		 AUD Appointments to Reschedule (appt)
                                                                                                        = ∫                                                                                                         AUD True Missed Appointment Rate- AUD Rescheduling Rate dt + AUD True Missed Appointment Rate* AUD Time to Reschedule
                                                                                                        Description: The number of appointments to be rescheduled. This assumes that all missed appointments are eventually rescheduled. (appts)
                                                                                                        Present In 1 View:
                                                                                                        • Model
                                                                                                        Used By
                                                                                                        • AUD Rescheduling Rate The rescheduling rate depends on the total number of appointments to reschedule and the average time it takes to reschedule them. (appts/wk)
                                                                                                        Feedback Loops: 1 (5.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 1  [2,2]
                                                                                                        mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #33
                                                                                                        L                                                                                                        		 AUD Patients in MM (pts)
                                                                                                        = ∫                                                                                                         AUD Starting Rate- AUD Ending Rate dt + AUD Initial Patients
                                                                                                        Description: The total number of patients in medication management. (pts)
                                                                                                        Present In 1 View:
                                                                                                        • Model
                                                                                                        Used By
                                                                                                        • AUD Booking Rate The booking rate combines demand from both existing patients (based on appointments on the calendar and the scheduled RVI) and new patients' first appointments. (appt/wk)
                                                                                                        • AUD Ending Rate The number of patients finishing medication management is a function the number of patients in treatment and their median time engaged in treatment. (pts/wk)
                                                                                                        Feedback Loops: 1 (5.0%) (+) 0  [0,0] (-) 1  [2,2]
                                                                                                        mm_i_v37_2024_06_18_v4 #51
                                                                                                        L                                                                                                        		 AUD Waiting to Start (pts)
                                                                                                        = ∫                                                                                                         AUD Referral Rate- AUD Starting Rate dt + AUD Initial Patients Waiting to Start
                                                                                                        Description: The total number of patients waiting to start medication management. (pts)
                                                                                                        Present In 1 View:
                                                                                                        • Model
                                                                                                        Used By
                                                                                                        • AUD Maximum Start Rate The maximum new patient start rate is determined by the new patient waiting list and minimum time to schedule patient appointments.
